le?<br /><br />Halleluja. Yes, they fixed it. And maybe that implies that POSIX will fix<br />it too (or maybe they _have_ fixed it, and nobody told me even though I<br />complained to them).<br /><br />Using a seprate "socklen_t" is fine, because that allows existing<br />implementations (and any new implementations that want to be able to run<br />standard BSD programs instead of running the imaginary programs that are<br />written to POSIX specs) to just make socklen_t be the same size as "int".<br /><br />You couldn't reasonably have done the same with "size_t", because you<br />really want to have a size_t that can span most of your address space. <br /><br />(The 32-bit minumum size would still mean that 16-bit UNIXen have problems<br />with trying to be Unix98 branded, but I have to say that that doesn't<br />strike me as being a major problem in this day and age ;) <br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
